Key takeaways.

Every recursive function needs a base case to stop and a recursive case that moves toward the base case. A missing base case means infinite recursion and a stack overflow.

Each recursive call pushes a stack frame. Frames are popped in last-in, first-out order as functions return — the call stack is a stack.

Memoization caches the result of each unique subproblem, converting exponential recursion trees into linear work. Python's l-r-u cache decorator and a Kotlin mutable map both implement this pattern.

Python's default recursion limit is one thousand frames. For deep recursion, convert to an explicit stack. Divide and conquer, structural recursion, and mathematical recursion are the three most common shapes — and you can always replace recursion with an explicit stack plus a loop.
